Calls two plotting functions (assumed defined elsewhere).

Any error is swallowed; function still returns a text message.

Nice UX: charts are optional, not required.

7) Helper to format one day‚Äôs message cleanly
def format_single_day_response(day_data, label, location, attribute):
    if not day_data:
        return f"Sorry, I don't have {label.lower()}'s forecast for {location}."

    if attribute == "temperature":
        return f"üå° {label} in {location}: {day_data['mintempC']}¬∞C ‚Äì {day_data['maxtempC']}¬∞C."
    elif attribute == "precipitation":
        return f"üåß {label} in {location}: {day_data.get('precipMM', '0')} mm precipitation expected."
    else:
        return (
            f"üìÖ {label} in {location}: "
            f"Temperature {day_data['mintempC']}¬∞C‚Äì{day_data['maxtempC']}¬∞C, "
            f"Precipitation {day_data.get('precipMM', '0')} mm."
        )


If day_data is missing ‚Üí apologetic message.

Otherwise:

temperature: shows min‚Äìmax ¬∞C.

precipitation: shows mm (uses .get with default ‚Äú0‚Äù).

general: shows both.

‚ö†Ô∏è Note: This uses day_data['mintempC'] and ['maxtempC'] directly; if those keys are missing, it will throw a KeyError. Consider changing to .get('mintempC') with a default to be safer.

8) Build the final response based on time_period
